answers.body_markdown:
An `Optional` could either contain an object or not. It does not matter what is in there.

Generally, `.get()` gives you the object which is wrapped in the `Optional`. But if there is no object (it wraps a `null`), you would get an exception.

To check whether the object in there is present, you could just say `OptionalObject.isPresent()`. This returns a `boolean` which tells you whether the `OptionalObject` actually wraps an object.

```
if(fetchList.isEmpty()) {
    throw new RuntimeException();
    // Consider not to throw RuntimeExceptions (see comments below)
}
// Continue your programme
```

Actually, `.isEmpty()` is only available since Java 11. In previous versions this could be achieved by negating `.isPresent()`.

```
if(!fetchList.isPresent()) {
    throw new RuntimeException();
}
// Continue your programme
```

Another, for this situation shorter and easier option is the by @ernest_k suggested one. It gets the element wrapped in the `Optional`. If the `Optional` is empty, the exception mentioned in the `.orElseThrow()` gets thrown. Furthermore, the lambda expression could be converted to a method reference (consider a good exception).

```
AbcDTO abcDTO = fetchList.orElseThrow(RuntimeException::new);
```

Anyway, this code checks only whether the `List` object is present. For checking further whether the existing `List` has no entries, you could call `.isEmpty()` for the list (not only for the `Optional`).

```
if(abcDTO.isEmpty()) {
    throw new RuntimeException();
}
```

