It depends on the complexity of the your custom control, if you have to handle a lot of business logic/data inside it, then that view should have its own view model

To think of it like this, in the application we have view controllers, a view controller is just a view, and we have a view model for it. So when the view controller is so complicated, we can divide it into smaller views with their own view models, a table view cell can have its view model if needed, it&#39;s similar to your case here.

So we might have a view model like this

    class CustomControlViewModel: NSObject {
        var data: String!
        var flag: Int!
    
        init(data: String, flag: Int) {
            self.data = data
            self.flag = flag
        }
    }

And the data is controlled inside the ViewControllerViewModel

    func createCustomControlViewModel() -&gt; CustomControlViewModel {
        return CustomControlViewModel(data: &quot;data from view model&quot;, flag: 1)
    }

