If your SQL query returns no result, `$d` will return `NULL` and the while-loop will end before it starts. Therefore none of the echo statements in the loop will be run.

Given the screenshot in [this comment](https://stackoverflow.com/questions/58229706/echo-inside-if-else-in-php/58231280#comment102836325_58229706), I think this is the case. That is why your if-then never ran in the case intended and shows nothing:

![https://i.ibb.co/5kfzXpP/Contoh.png](https://i.ibb.co/5kfzXpP/Contoh.png)

As [@catcon](https://stackoverflow.com/users/11430357/catcon) mentioned in [comment](https://stackoverflow.com/questions/58229706/echo-inside-if-else-in-php/58231280#comment102833948_58229706), you can use [mysqli_num_row](https://www.php.net/mysqli_num_rows) to check if there is any result at all. That way you may still show something when there is no result:

```php
&lt;?php
    $kata=&#39;&#39;;
    $no=1;
    $data = mysqli_query($koneksi,&quot;SELECT msdosen.`IDDOSEN`, `POSITION`, 
        `COMPANY`, `START`, `END` 
        FROM trprofessionalhis 
        INNER JOIN msdosen ON msdosen.IDDOSEN = trprofessionalhis.IDDOSEN 
        WHERE trprofessionalhis.IDDOSEN =&#39;$id&#39; 
        ORDER BY trprofessionalhis.`START` DESC&quot;);

    // add this to print &quot;-&quot; if the query returns no result
    if (mysqli_num_row($data) &lt;= 0) {
        echo &#39;&lt;br&gt; -&#39;;
    }
?&gt;
&lt;?php while($d = mysqli_fetch_array($data)) { ?&gt;
    &lt;br&gt;&lt;?php echo $d[&#39;POSITION&#39;];?&gt;&lt;br&gt;&lt;?php echo $d[&#39;COMPANY&#39;];?&gt;
    &lt;br&gt;&lt;?php echo $d[&#39;START&#39;];?&gt;-&lt;?php echo $d[&#39;END&#39;]?&gt;
&lt;?php } ?&gt;
```

You can use ternary operator. Here is example:&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;code&gt;echo empty($d[&#39;POSITION&#39;]) ? $d[&#39;POSITION&#39;] : &#39;-&#39;;&lt;/code&gt;

If you are using PHP 7+ version, there is more short way:&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;code&gt;echo $d[&#39;POSITION&#39;] ?? &#39;-&#39;;&lt;/code&gt;

More [examples][1] about ternary operator.


  [1]: https://www.php.net/manual/en/migration70.new-features.php#migration70.new-features.null-coalesce-op

