PHP&#39;s [list](https://www.php.net/list) syntax takes the right side of the assignment operator `=`, destructure it, then assign the children to the variables in it.

A list statement like this:

```php
list($name, $password) = $some_array;
```

Expects `$some_array` to be a numerical array with at least 2 children in it. If there is only 1, PHP would complain you&#39;re missing the 2nd item (offset 1). In your case, the explode call would require a `:` colon in the result of your [base64_decode](https://www.php.net/base64_decode) result, which might not be the case.

To prevent this, you may modify it to not directly destructure the result of your [explode](https://www.php.net/explode) call. Like this:

```php
if (isset($_SERVER[&#39;HTTP_AUTHORIZATION&#39;]) &amp;&amp; preg_match(&#39;/Basic\s+(.*)$/i&#39;, $_SERVER[&#39;HTTP_AUTHORIZATION&#39;], $matches)) {
        $name_and_password = explode(&#39;:&#39;, base64_decode($matches[1]));
        $name = $name_and_password[0] ?? &#39;&#39;; // if not set, default to be empty string &#39;&#39;
        $password = $name_and_password[1] ?? &#39;&#39;; // if not set, default to be empty string &#39;&#39;
        $_SERVER[&#39;PHP_AUTH_USER&#39;] = strip_tags($name);
}
```

